<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-194-310 </DOCNO><DOCID>10 542 957</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  March 26 1991* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1991.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Atari sales drop 11% in 4q. (4th quarter of 1990)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Woods, Wendy.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Atari Computer Corp. (Earnings).andO;Topic:     SalesFourth QuarterFinancial ReportRevenue.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>****ATARI SALES DROP 11% IN 4Q 03/26/91 SUNNYVALE, CALIFORNIA, U.S.A., 1991MAR 26 (NB) -- Atari posted disappointing results for its fourth quarterending December 31, 1990.andP;  The firm says fourth quarter sales dropped 11% to$151.9 million, compared to the like quarter a year ago.andM;The decline is blamed on the Persian Gulf war, but Atari President SamTramiel is looking on the bright side, &quot;Although sales in the fourth quarterwere understandably disappointing, the company continues to strengthen itsbalance sheet.andP;  The Atari STE and TT030 computer line, based on Motorola's68000 and 68030 microprocessors, continues to be a cornerstone of ourbusiness.&quot;andM;Tramiel says that at the recent Consumer Electronics Show, Atari cut theprice on its Lynx hand-held game machine.andP;  The new price is $99.andP;  SaysTramiel: &quot;This new price point, together with an expanded range of softwaretitles, makes Lynx an even stronger competitor in the portable video gamemarket.&quot;andM;Atari says net income for the quarter was $8.8 million.andP;  Sales for the 12months ended 1990 were $411.5 million, a decrease of 3% compared to sales of$423.6 million during 1989.andP;  Net income for 1990 was $14.9 million versus $4million for 1989.andM;(Wendy Woods/19910326/Press Contact: August Ligouri, Atari, 408-745-5460)</TEXT></DOC>